    <p><strong>Note:</strong> You can claim these fees back from the tenant if you win, but actually collecting them may be difficult if they have no money.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>Step 4: Submit to Court</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Online:</strong> Some courts accept online submissions via HMCTS portal</li>
    <li><strong>Post:</strong> Send to your local county court (find via <a href="https://www.gov.uk/find-court-tribunal">gov.uk/find-court-tribunal</a>)</li>
    <li><strong>In Person:</strong> Hand deliver to court office during business hours</li>
  </ul>

  <p><strong>Processing Time:</strong> Court will usually acknowledge within 2-5 working days and set a hearing date within 4-8 weeks.</p>

  <h3>Step 5: Prepare for Court Hearing</h3>

  {{#if (eq notice_route "section_21")}}
    {{#if accelerated_procedure}}
      <div class="info-box">
        <strong>Accelerated Procedure:</strong> Usually no hearing. Judge reviews paperwork only. If everything perfect, you get possession order by post within 6-8 weeks. If issues, judge may call a hearing or reject outright.
      </div>
    {{else}}
      <p>Your hearing will be scheduled 4-8 weeks after application. You MUST attend (or have a representative attend).</p>
    {{/if}}
  {{else}}
    <p>Section 8 hearings are usually scheduled 4-8 weeks after application. You MUST attend (or have a representative attend).</p>
  {{/if}}

  <h4>What to Bring to Hearing:</h4>
  <ul>
    <li>‚úì All evidence (original documents + 3 copies)</li>
    <li>‚úì Witness statements (if applicable)</li>
    <li>‚úì Photos of property damage (if claiming for that)</li>
    <li>‚úì Rent account ledger showing arrears</li>
    <li>‚úì Copy of notice and proof of service</li>
    <li>‚úì Any correspondence with tenant</li>
  </ul>

  <h4>What Happens at Hearing:</h4>
  <ol>
    <li>Judge reviews your evidence</li>
    <li>Tenant can defend (rare, but they might claim you didn't serve properly or notice invalid)</li>
    <li>Judge asks questions</li>
    <li>Judge makes decision (usually same day)</li>
  </ol>

  <div class="success">
    <strong>Success Rate:</strong> If you've followed all steps correctly and have proper evidence, possession is usually granted. {{#if (eq notice_route "section_8")}}For mandatory grounds (like Ground 8 with 2+ months arrears), judge MUST grant possession if proven.{{/if}}
  </div>

  <h3>Step 6: After Possession Order Granted</h3>

  <p>If judge grants possession, the tenant gets:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>14 days to leave</strong> (standard)</li>
    <li><strong>28 days to leave</strong> (if judge grants extended time due to hardship)</li>
    <li><strong>42 days maximum</strong> (in exceptional circumstances)</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="warning">
    ‚ö†Ô∏è <strong>Still Can't Force Them Out:</strong> Even with a possession order, you still can't change locks or force the tenant out yourself. If they don't leave by the court-ordered date, proceed to Step 7.
  </div>

  <h3>Step 7: Apply for Bailiff Warrant (If Needed)</h3>

  <p>If tenant still hasn't left after the possession order deadline:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Fill in Form N325:</strong> Request for bailiff warrant</li>
    <li><strong>Pay ¬£130 fee</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Submit to court</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Wait 2-4 weeks:</strong> Bailiff appointment scheduled</li>
    <li><strong>Eviction Day:</strong> County court bailiff physically removes tenant and their belongings</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="info-box">
    ‚ÑπÔ∏è <strong>Bailiff Eviction:</strong> Only a county court bailiff can physically evict someone. They will attend the property, remove the tenant and possessions, change the locks, and hand keys to you. The tenant's belongings are typically left on the street (unless weather is very bad, in which case they may be stored for a short period).
  </div>

